        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Russians will face fines upto $64 <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-jul-25-spotlight-h1-1-consuming-extremist-content?source=website" target="_blank">consuming “extremist” content</a> online as per the latest legislation. It targets users who browse content from 5,473 registered extremist entries and enables law enforcement agencies to demand users' browsing data from telecoms and mobile operators. The legislation also criminalizes the advertising of VPN services.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> Russian authorities have ramped up a crackdown on dissent and digital liberty since the 2022 Russia-Ukraine war. Independent news outlets and rights groups were accused of being foreign agents and were outlawed. There is also an increase in online censorship and prosecutions for social media posts and comments.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px";>
            <strong>The bigger picture:</strong> The vague definition of “extremism” could enable the authorities to target minorities and political opposition. Experts recommend avoiding Russian browsers, using reliable VPN providers, and deactivating biometric identification features to escape surveillance. Russian authorities are also considering additional restrictions, which could result in a <a style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              " href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-23-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-ban-on-whatsapp?source=website" target="_blank">ban on WhatsApp</a>.
          </p>
